diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys don't work as well as they should. It can affect anyone, but it's more common in people who are black or of south Asian origin.
A disorder characterized by patterns of inattention or impulsivity that are not consistent with the individual's developmental level. It may contribute to hyperactivity symptoms.
An infection or inflammation of the middle ear. It is common in children but can occur at any age. The condition can be acute or chronic.
A condition where ulcers form on the lining of the stomach or the first part of the small intestine. Stress and spicy foods don’t cause peptic ulcers, but they can make symptoms worse.
A group of disorders where the body's immune defense system is impaired, leading to an increased susceptibility to infections. It can be primary (congenital) or secondary (acquired).

A disease where there is too much sugar in the blood because the body cannot use it properly. It can cause damage to organs and tissues over time, including the kidneys, increasing the risk of chronic kidney disease.
High blood pressure can damage the kidneys over time, leading to chronic kidney disease. It is often associated with other chronic conditions.
A condition in which there aren't enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to the body's tissues, often seen in chronic kidney disease.
A digestive disorder where stomach acid or, occasionally, stomach content, flows back into your esophagus (acid reflux), which can lead to erosive esophagitis and ulcers.

An autoimmune disease where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks healthy tissue. It can affect the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs, potentially leading to chronic kidney disease and increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: COVID-19
diagnoses.reasoning: COVID-19 can cause dysgeusia as a common symptom, and can also lead to pneumonia. Lymphadenopathy has been associated with COVID-19 in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Iron deficiency anemia could explain hypoferritinemia. Though less directly related, anemia could exacerbate the symptoms or outcomes of other conditions like infections or arteriovenous malformations.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia (HHT)
diagnoses.reasoning: This genetic disorder causes arteriovenous malformations and could potentially explain episodes of iron deficiency (hypoferritinemia) due to bleeding. Pneumonia and lymphadenopathy could be secondary complications.

diagnoses.name: Cat Scratch Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Caused by Bartonella henselae, this disease can lead to lymphadenopathy. In rare cases, it might be associated with other symptoms listed due to systemic infection.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Sarcoidosis can cause lymphadenopathy and has been associated with pulmonary issues (pneumonia-like symptoms). It can cause systemic issues that might indirectly relate to other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.reasoning: This bacterial infection primarily affects the lungs (causing pneumonia) but can also cause generalized lymphadenopathy. It may indirectly lead to systemic symptoms including dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain types of lymphoma could explain the lymphadenopathy and could indirectly cause pulmonary symptoms. Depending on the type and stage, it might also contribute to or be associated with other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Infective Endocarditis
diagnoses.reasoning: This infection of the heart valves can cause systemic symptoms such as dysgeusia and could potentially lead to arteriovenous malformations due to the creation of septic emboli. Pneumonia might be a secondary infection in this case.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune disorder that can cause systemic symptoms including those affecting the lungs (pneumonia) and lymph nodes (lymphadenopathy). It can also lead to iron deficiency anemia.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including hematologic abnormalities (hypoferritinemia), lymphadenopathy, and lung involvement (pneumonia).
